CPP Module 01 - Memory Allocation, Pointers to Members, File Streams
This module of the C++ pool at 42 School focuses on deepening the understanding of memory management, the difference between pointers and references, and the usage of file streams and pointers to member functions.

📋 Projects Overview
Ex00: BraiiiiiiinnnzzzZ

Goal: Learn about Stack vs Heap allocation.

Key Concept: Understanding when an object should be allocated on the stack (automatic destruction) or the heap (manual management using new and delete).

Ex01: Moar Brainz!

Goal: Allocate an array of objects.

Key Concept: Using new[] to allocate a "Horde" of Zombies and ensuring a single delete[] is used to prevent memory leaks.

Ex02: HI THIS IS BRAIN

Goal: Compare Pointers and References.

Key Concept: Understanding that a Reference is just an alias to an existing variable, while a Pointer is a variable that stores a memory address.

Ex03: Unnecessary Violence

Goal: Use pointers and references as class attributes.

Key Concept: HumanA uses a Reference (must have a weapon at all times), while HumanB uses a Pointer (can start unarmed and change weapons later).

Ex04: Sed is for Losers

Goal: File manipulation and string replacement.

Key Concept: Using std::ifstream and std::ofstream to read a file and create a .replace copy without using the forbidden std::string::replace function.

Ex05: Harl 2.0

Goal: Avoid "if/else" forests.

Key Concept: Implementing Pointers to Member Functions. Using an array of pointers to jump directly to the correct private method (debug, info, warning, error).

Ex06: Harl Filter

Goal: Implement a log level filter.

Key Concept: Using the switch statement with fall-through logic to display messages of a certain severity level and everything above it.